  "prompt": "Does the government have laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, the U.S. government has numerous laws against money laundering. Here are some of the most important ones:\n\n*   **Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) of 1970:** This is the foundational U.S. anti-money laundering (AML) law. It requires financial institutions to keep records and file reports on transactions that might indicate money laundering or other financial crimes.\n*   **Money Laundering Control Act of 1986:** This act made money laundering a federal crime. It prohibits knowingly engaging in financial transactions with the proceeds of illegal activity.\n*   **Annunzio-Wylie Anti-Money Laundering Act of 1992:** This act expanded the reach of the BSA and increased penalties for money laundering violations.\n*   **USA PATRIOT Act of 2001:** Passed in response to the September 11th attacks, this act significantly strengthened AML laws. It expanded the definition of financial institutions subject to AML requirements, increased due diligence requirements for financial institutions, and enhanced information sharing between law enforcement and financial institutions.\n\nThese laws are enforced by various agencies, including:\n\n*   **Financial Crimes Enforcement Network (FinCEN):** A bureau of the U.S. Department of the Treasury. FinCEN is the primary regulator for AML compliance.\n*   **Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI):** Investigates money laundering and related crimes.\n*   **Drug Enforcement Administration (DEA):** Investigates money laundering related to drug trafficking.\n*   **Internal Revenue Service - Criminal Investigation (IRS-CI):** Investigates money laundering related to tax evasion and other financial crimes.\n\nThe penalties for money laundering can be severe, including substantial fines and imprisonment.\n\n**Disclaimer:** I am an AI Chatbot and not a financial expert, lawyer, or legal professional. Seek out guidance from a professional when needed.",
